    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7e44a3d0-1bca-497e-b724-3cc351aa6671",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 55-year-old man with a sturdy, overweight build and a mildly antalgic gait, often shifting weight off his more painful knee when standing for long periods. He works as a warehouse supervisor, a job that still requires long stretches of walking the floor, climbing short flights of stairs, and occasional lifting despite his managerial role. Over the past several years he has developed gradually worsening knee pain with brief morning stiffness, stiffness after sitting, and difficulty with prolonged standing. He often rubs the knee unconsciously during conversation and reports intermittent swelling, a grinding sensation, pain with stair climbing, and discomfort that is usually worse by the end of the workday and in cold, damp weather. He also notices reduced knee range of motion and has increasing difficulty rising from low chairs, kneeling, and squatting.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his spouse and remains closely involved with his adult children and a small circle of longtime friends. He enjoys weekend grilling, watching football, and light gardening, though kneeling, crouching, and going up and down stairs have become increasingly difficult. He used to play recreational basketball in his 30s and 40s and still tries to stay active with short walks, but his mobility has become more limited because of knee discomfort, crepitus, and pain after longer distances. He occasionally avoids social outings that involve a lot of walking or standing.\n\nDespite these limitations, {patientName} is generally independent in activities of daily living. He sleeps reasonably well but sometimes wakes when turning in bed causes knee discomfort. He denies systemic symptoms such as fever, night sweats, or unexplained weight loss. His mood is mildly frustrated rather than depressed; he is concerned that reduced mobility is affecting both his work endurance and his ability to keep up with household tasks.\n\nHis appearance is otherwise well kept and age appropriate. He wears practical work clothes and supportive shoes, and he has recently started using an over-the-counter elastic knee brace during busier work shifts. Friends and family describe him as reliable and stoic, the type who tends to downplay symptoms until they interfere with routine life, which is why he is now seeking more structured medical evaluation. Outside of work he has spent years doing home projects and gardening that involve prolonged crouching and kneeling, and he recognizes that these repetitive joint-loading habits, along with weight gain over time, tend to flare his pain."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:72b3915d-3f41-42ea-9931-53eabbcfee96",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports a several-year history of gradually progressive knee pain, worse with prolonged standing, walking long distances, stair climbing, kneeling, squatting, and the end of the workday. He recalls no single major trauma but did play recreational basketball for many years and has spent decades in physically demanding jobs involving repetitive lifting, walking, kneeling, stair climbing, and frequent pivoting while carrying loads. He notes brief morning stiffness, stiffness after inactivity, a grinding sensation in the knee, intermittent mild swelling, and progressive difficulty rising from low chairs, but denies true locking, acute instability, fevers, rash, or other inflammatory joint symptoms.\n\nHis medical history is notable for essential hypertension and seasonal allergic rhinitis. He has not been diagnosed with rheumatologic disease, septic arthritis, or crystal arthropathy. He was evaluated in an urgent care setting two years ago for worsening knee pain after a particularly busy work week, but no fracture or acute injury was identified. He has never been hospitalized for joint disease. He uses occasional over-the-counter ibuprofen and a knee brace with partial relief, and he previously had a corticosteroid injection with temporary improvement.\n\nLifestyle factors include a mostly sedentary evening routine after physically active workdays. He is overweight, which likely contributes additional biomechanical stress to the knee joint. In addition to his warehouse work, he frequently does yard work and home maintenance that involve crouching, kneeling on hard surfaces, and repeated stair use, and he has noticed that these repetitive joint-loading activities consistently trigger symptom flares. He does not currently smoke, having quit in his early 40s after a light smoking history, and he drinks alcohol socially, typically 1 to 2 beers on weekends. His diet is mixed and he admits he could improve portion control and regular exercise, but knee pain has made sustained activity harder.\n\nHe remains independent in self-care and continues to work full time, though he has started modifying tasks and delegating more physically demanding duties. He has no history suggestive of inflammatory polyarthritis or malignancy. His goals are to reduce pain, preserve mobility, lose weight to reduce joint stress, and continue working without needing early retirement."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}